h and clarity in an area of murky ambiguity, producing a much-needed standard at the border of science, philosophy, and psychology. . . . As he presents his case, offering a forthright critique of past and present theories, Griffiths touches on such issues as evolution, social construction, natural kinds (categories corresponding with real distinctions in nature), cognition, and moods. While addressing specialists, the book will reward general readers who apply themselves to its remarkably accessible style."—Library Journal "What Emotions Really Are makes a strong claim to be one of the best books to have emerged on the subject of human emotion."—Ray Dolan, Nature  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEmotions. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh  aemotion, affect, psychology, philosophy, evolution, neurobiology, cognitive science, cognition, social construction, moods, nature, biology, mental health, adaptive mechanisms, sociobiology, gabriele taylor, nussbaum, kenny, solomon, humanity, feelings, love, shame, desire, anger, connection, relationships, society, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226308760423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226308760/original  a978-3-11-066785-1  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles